{
  "name": "RAG_Mistral",
  "nodes": [
    {
      "parameters": {
        "content": "### The Full RAG Pipeline Detailed way\n\nUnderstanding the complete RAG pipeline is essential. \n\nHere is the step-by-step flow from document to answer:\n\n### Phase 1: Indexing (Offline / One-Time/ Continues) | Ingestion\n- **Step 1 – Load:** Document loaders read PDFs, DOCX, HTML, CSVs, databases, APIs, etc.\n- **Step 2 – Transform:** Clean text, remove headers/footers, normalize formatting.\n- **Step 3 – Chunk:** Split documents into chunks using a chosen strategy.\n- **Step 4 – Embed:** Convert each chunk to a vector using an embedding model.\n- **Step 5 – Store:** Save vectors + text + metadata in a vector database.\n\n\n### Phase 2: Retrieval + Generation (Online / Per Query)\n- **Step 6 – Query Embed:** User's question is converted to a vector using the SAME embedding model.\n- **Step 7 – Search:** Vector database performs similarity search, returns **top-K chunks.**\n- **Step 8 – Augment:** Retrieved chunks are injected into the LLM prompt as context.\n- **Step 9 – Generate:** LLM generates a response grounded in the retrieved context.\n- **Step 10 – (Optional) Cite:** System references which source documents the answer came from.\n⚠️ **Critical Rule:** The embedding model used for indexing MUST be the same model used for querying. \n\nIf you embed documents with \"nomic-embed-text\" but query with \"text-embedding-3-small\", the vectors live in different mathematical spaces and similarity search will return garbage.\n\n",
        "height": 144,
        "width": 336
      },
      "type": "n8n-nodes-base.stickyNote",
      "position": [
        -128,
        -208
      ],
      "typeVersion": 1,
      "id": "42703de0-f898-4bf7-bd67-621ebc862afe",
      "name": "Sticky Note"
    },
